---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .obj-card { border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 20px 22px; background: var(--card); margin-bottom: 16px; }
    .obj-header { display: flex; align-items: baseline; justify-content: space-between; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .obj-num { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; color: var(--text-muted); letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .obj-title { font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0; }
    .obj-purpose { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 13.5px; margin: 6px 0 12px 0; line-height: 1.55; }
    .obj-fields { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; background: var(--muted); padding: 10px 14px; border-radius: 6px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; overflow-x: auto; }
    .obj-why { font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--text-muted); border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle); padding-top: 10px; margin-top: 12px; font-style: italic; }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="20 · Protocol Objects — Sardis Canvas" currentId="protocol-objects">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 20 · Protocol</span>
        <h1>Protocol Objects — the 10 signed artifacts.</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Sardis v1.0 defines 10 protocol objects that chain together from delegation through settlement,
          dispute resolution, and fulfillment. Every object is cryptographically signed, immutable once issued,
          and references its predecessors. Together they form a complete audit chain — no trust in Sardis required.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          A reusable funding credential — card, wallet, bank credential, or API key — is the wrong primitive for
          the agent economy. The right primitive is the <strong>One-Time Payment Object</strong>: a signed,
          short-lived, context-bound instrument backed by a UTXO-style funding commitment, tied to a verified
          agent and principal, bounded by policy, and auditable with a complete cryptographic trail.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Object chain</div>
          <h2>From delegation to fulfillment in 10 objects.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">1 · Agent Certificate</h3><span class="obj-num">Identity</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Identifies the agent and binds it to an issuer and a principal context. Without cryptographic agent identity, you don't have agent payments — you have bot payments. TAP-compatible so agents can prove identity to any Visa-network merchant.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">agent_id · issuer_id · principal_id · agent_public_key (Ed25519 or P-256 JWK)<br>attestation_type (self_signed | issuer_attested | network_verified)<br>trust_tier (0–3) · capabilities (browse, pay, subscribe, delegate) · expires_at · signature</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Trust tiers:</strong> 0 = unverified ($10 max tx, email only) · 1 = issuer-attested ($500, KYC-lite) · 2 = network-verified ($10K, full KYC + TAP) · 3 = enterprise-grade (policy-defined, full IAM + continuous monitoring).</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">2 · Spending Mandate</h3><span class="obj-num">Authorization</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">The signed statement of allowed authority from the principal — a programmable, cryptographically signed power of attorney for spending. Heart of the system. Expressible as an AP2 Verifiable Digital Credential, extended with agent-native fields (in_flight_limit, fx_policy, UTXO cell strategy).</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">mandate_id · principal_id · agent_id · merchant_scope · category_scope<br>max_amount_per_tx · max_amount_per_period · period_type (daily | weekly | monthly)<br>currency_scope · rail_scope · approval_threshold · retry_limit<br><strong>in_flight_limit</strong> · fx_policy · valid_from · expires_at · policy_hash<br>revocation_handle · nonce · signature (Ed25519/P-256)</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Security — in_flight_limit:</strong> prevents the T4 "shadow lock" attack where a malfunctioning agent freezes all funds by requesting objects without presenting them. Agent must settle or cancel before minting new objects beyond the limit.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">3 · Funding Commitment</h3><span class="obj-num">Reserve</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Reserve-backed container bound to a specific mandate. Guarantees funds are available before any payment object is minted. In v0 this was a monolithic lock against a vault balance — v1 replaces it with a UTXO model to allow concurrent spending without race conditions.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">commitment_id · mandate_id<br>funding_source_type (custodial_fiat | smart_wallet | card | bank | stablecoin | credit_line)<br>funding_source_ref · total_committed · cell_strategy (pre_split | on_demand | hybrid)<br>default_cell_denomination · commitment_expiry · settlement_preferences<br>fallback_options · <strong>refund_destination</strong> · issuer_signature</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Security — refund_destination:</strong> must always point to a permanent Principal Master Treasury, never a temp vault or cell. Prevents the T6 "refund-to-closed-vault" failure where disputes resolve months after the original transaction and the funding container is gone.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">4 · FundingCell (UTXO)</h3><span class="obj-num">Concurrency</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">A discrete, atomic unit of spendable value within a Funding Commitment. Inspired by Bitcoin's UTXO model: each cell has exactly one owner at any time; concurrent payments claim different cells; double-spending is structurally impossible without distributed consensus.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">cell_id (primary key for locking) · commitment_id · mandate_id<br>denomination (fixed) · state (AVAILABLE | CLAIMED | SPENT | RETURNED | EXPIRED | SPLIT | MERGED)<br>claimed_by · claimed_at · payment_object_id · parent_cell_id · vault_ref<br>created_at · expires_at · nonce · issuer_signature</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Why it beats a global counter:</strong> no distributed locking. PostgreSQL <code>FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED</code> ensures concurrent transactions never block each other. Cells split on-demand (an agent needing $7 from a $10 cell produces $7 CLAIMED + $3 AVAILABLE), merge in background to prevent fragmentation. Horizontally scalable.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">5 · One-Time Payment Object</h3><span class="obj-num">Execution</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">The single-use executable payment artifact — what the agent presents to the merchant. Derived from the mandate + funding commitment cell(s). Every payment creates a fresh object; no credential is ever reused. This is the core innovation of the protocol.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">payment_object_id · mandate_id · commitment_id · cell_ids (UTXO inputs)<br>merchant_id · <strong>session_hash</strong> (sha256: merchant_id | cart_id | timestamp)<br>exact_amount · source_currency · target_currency · nonce · one_time_use (true)<br>expires_at (minutes–hours) · privacy_mode (transparent | hybrid | full_zk)<br>zk_proof (if non-transparent) · escrow_required · escrow_profile · dispute_profile<br>signature_chain [principal_sig, issuer_sig, agent_sig]</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Security — session_hash:</strong> binds payment to a specific merchant session/cart. Prevents the T3 relay/MITM attack where an intermediary intercepts a valid payment and replays it in a different shopping context.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">6 · Settlement Receipt</h3><span class="obj-num">Proof</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Canonical proof of what actually happened. Closes the audit chain. v1 adds fulfillment_status to track whether the agent acknowledged receipt of the purchased service/good, plus FX fields for cross-currency transactions.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">receipt_id · payment_object_id · settlement_rail · settlement_tx_ref<br>settled_amount · fees · fx_quote_id · actual_fx_rate · fx_fee<br>timestamp · status (settled | partial_settled | failed | reversed)<br><strong>fulfillment_status</strong> (pending_ack | acknowledged | dispute_auto_triggered)<br>merchant_signature · network_signature</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>fulfillment_status (new in v1):</strong> if not acknowledged within escrow timeout, dispute_auto_triggered fires automatically. Closes the T11 "paid but not delivered" gap — settlement succeeds but merchant fails to provide the service.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">7 · EscrowHold</h3><span class="obj-num">Trust</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">For transactions above the escrow threshold, funds land in escrow before the merchant receives them. Merchant sees cryptographic proof of locked funds and delivers the service; agent confirms receipt (or timelock expires); then escrow releases. If dispute: arbitration decides.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">escrow_id · payment_object_id · held_amount<br>held_at (issuer_vault | smart_contract) · contract_address · beneficiary<br>release_condition (AGENT_CONFIRM | TIMELOCK | ORACLE) · timeout_duration · auto_release_at<br>state (HELD | CONFIRMING | AUTO_RELEASING | RELEASED | DISPUTING | ARBITRATING | RESOLVED_*)<br>dispute_window · evidence_deadline · arbitration_endpoint · issuer_signature</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Default timeouts by transaction type:</strong> API/SaaS = 1h escrow, 24h dispute, 3-day evidence · Software license = 24h / 7d / 5d · Physical goods = 14d / 30d / 7d · B2B services = 30d / 60d / 14d. Timeouts match delivery verification complexity.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">8 · FXQuote</h3><span class="obj-num">Cross-currency</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Records the cross-currency conversion applied during settlement. Linked from the Settlement Receipt. Time-bounded quote with explicit slippage tracking.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">fx_quote_id · source_currency · target_currency<br>quoted_rate · quoted_at · quote_valid_until (default 30s)<br>source_amount · target_amount · fx_fee · total_source_debit<br>slippage_actual_bps · provider · provider_tx_ref</div>
          <div class="obj-why">Matched against the mandate's <code>fx_policy</code> at verification time. If <code>slippage_actual_bps</code> exceeds <code>max_slippage_bps</code> or the provider isn't in <code>preferred_fx_providers</code>, the payment fails before settlement.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">9 · Subscription</h3><span class="obj-num">Recurring</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Recurring charge intents + billing cycles + dunning rules. Not a single mandate but a parent that emits child one-time payment objects on schedule. Covers SaaS subscriptions, usage-based billing, and agent-mediated BNPL (credit-backed mandates).</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">subscription_id · parent_mandate_id · merchant_id<br>charge_intent · billing_cycle (ISO 8601 duration) · dunning_policy<br>amendment_protocol (price_creep_protection)<br>grace_period · usage_counter · countersignature (for usage-based)</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Price-creep protection:</strong> if the merchant issues an amendment that exceeds <code>mandate.amendment_tolerance_bps</code>, the subscription pauses pending principal re-signature. Prevents silent subscription inflation that consumer credit cards suffer from.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-card">
          <div class="obj-header"><h3 class="obj-title">10 · Mandate Tree</h3><span class="obj-num">Delegation</span></div>
          <div class="obj-purpose">Hierarchical delegation. CFO creates a master mandate ($500K/quarter); VP Engineering creates a child mandate ($100K/quarter) under it; team lead creates a grandchild ($20K/month). Each level further constrains — never expands — the parent's bounds. Maps to how enterprise budgets actually work.</div>
          <div class="obj-fields">tree_root_mandate_id · parent_mandate_id · depth · path<br>inherited_constraints (merchant_scope ∩, category_scope ∩, limits ≤ parent)<br>delegation_signature (parent signs child) · revocation_cascade</div>
          <div class="obj-why"><strong>Enforcement rule:</strong> child mandate constraints MUST be a strict subset of parent. Issuer rejects creation if any dimension expands. Revocation cascades down the tree — revoking a parent invalidates all descendants.</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Chain</div>
          <h2>How they reference each other.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Each object is signed and references its predecessors, forming a chain that any party can verify
            independently. Canvas <a href="/state-machine">21 · 22-State Machine</a> shows how these objects
            transition through states over time.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart LR
  AC[Agent Certificate] --> SM[Spending Mandate]
  SM --> FC[Funding Commitment]
  FC --> FCell[FundingCell UTXO]
  SM --> MT[Mandate Tree children]
  SM -. recurring .-> SUB[Subscription]
  FCell --> POO[One-Time Payment Object]
  SM --> POO
  POO --> EH[EscrowHold optional]
  POO --> SR[Settlement Receipt]
  SR --> FXQ[FXQuote if cross-currency]
  EH --> SR
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

